- [x] Create `src/render/index.ts` as the render orchestrator: takes `PackageHealth` and returns a `string` (the complete terminal output). No side effects — it returns the string, the CLI entry point prints it. The orchestrator imports helpers for each section of the output
- [x] Create `src/render/renderHeader/index.ts` — formats `pkg-pulse: <name>@<version>` and the overall score line with confidence percentage
- [x] Create `src/render/renderCategories/index.ts` — formats each category as a bar chart row (`renderBar` helper) with score, label, and detail strings. Uses Unicode block characters for the bar
- [x] Create `src/render/renderWarnings/index.ts` — formats the warnings section with severity icons
- [x] Create `src/render/renderFooter/index.ts` — formats data sources list, unavailable signals section, and the confidence advisory message when coverage is below 100%

### 7. CLI entry point — argument parsing, validation, orchestration

Read: `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`, `coding-playbook/services/error-handling`, `coding-playbook/services/service-layer`

- [x] Create `src/bin/index.ts`: the top-level orchestrator. Reads `process.argv` for the package name (no framework — simple positional arg parsing). Reads `GITHUB_TOKEN` from `process.env`. Validates the package name against npm naming rules (no special characters except `@` and `/` for scoped packages). Calls the fetch orchestrator, then the scoring engine, then the renderer, then prints to stdout. Sets exit codes per spec: 0 success, 1 not found, 2 total network failure, 3 invalid name
- [x] Create `src/bin/validatePackageName/index.ts` — pure function that validates npm package name format. Returns `{ valid: true, name: string }` or `{ valid: false, reason: string }`
- [x] Add a shebang `#!/usr/bin/env node` to the bin entry and ensure `package.json` bin field points to `./dist/bin/index.js`

